  Rules 1-102(a), 2-110(a)(3), 6-101(a)(3), 7-101(a) of the Code of Professional Responsibility and Rules 1.3 , 1.4 ,
  1.16 (d) and 8.4 of Professional Conduct in connection with Respondent's acceptance of a fee for representation in
  post conviction proceedings, failing to respond to client, and forcing legal action to obtain accounting return of
  unearned fees.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><u>Admonition, case no. 97-ADB-065, October 16, 1997</u>, violation of Rule 1.15 of
  Professional Conduct in connection with negligent mishandling of client funds that was subsequently corrected.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ednref6" name="_edn6" class="fn" id="_edn6">[vi]</a> Rule 1.5 is entitled "Fees"
  and provides in pertinent part:</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">"(f) Payment of fees in advance of services shall be subject to the following rules:</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">. . .</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">"(2) When the client pays the lawyer all or part of a fixed fee or of a minimum fee for
  particular representation with services to be rendered in the future, the funds become the property of the lawyer
  when paid, subject to the provisions of Rule 1.5 (f)(6). Such funds need not be placed in the lawyer's trust account,
  but may be placed in the lawyer's operating account."</p>
  <hr />

  <div id="concurLeake">
    <h2>CONCURRENCE</h2>

    <p class="Bodycopy">  The record does not reflect whether or not Respondent was served with the deemed admitted
    order. However, the H.C. report was served on Respondent and it made no finding of fact that is not contained in
    Respondent's response to Office of Disciplinary Counsel's inquiries prior to formal charges. Respondent has
    steadfastly ignored the disciplinary process after his first, rather extensive, response to the complaint. While I
    urge strict conformity with, and proof of, all notice requirements, Respondent does not seem to have been
    prejudiced. He was notified of the Board hearing but did not appear.</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy">I admit to being troubled by Respondent's history of prior discipline (six times), and also by
    Respondent's apparent cavalier attitude toward the disciplinary process. However, his initial response before
    charges were filed seems to have been complete, and he had made an accounting and refund to his clients,
    <u>before</u> the complaint was filed. Further, he discovered an error in that refund and made the further refund
    voluntarily.</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy">I can support finding a violation of Rules 1.15(a) and 1.16(d), but believe it was minimal and
    in good faith. I do not concur in finding a violation of Rule 8.4(a). It adds nothing to say that violation of
    Rules 1.15(a) and 1.16(d) constitutes a separate violation of Rule 8.4(a). This case does not involve an unrealized
    attempt to violate the rules, or assisting or inducing another to do so, or violation through the acts of another.
    I therefore dissent from the holding of a Rule 8.4(a) violation.</p>

    <p class="Bodycopy">I concur in the proposed sanction of a public reprimand.</p>

    <p class="signature">New Orleans, February 7, 2001.</p>

    <p class="signature"><span class="Author">Robert E. Leake, Jr.</span></p>
